{:metadata {:description [{"text" "<p>This entry represents VapB from enteric bacteria and related proteins that are part of the VapBC toxin-antitoxin system. Toxin-antitoxin (TA) systems are common in prokaryotes and allow cells to rapidly adapt to changing environmental conditions through release of active regulators of metabolism. For enteric vapBC TA, the VapC toxins specifically cleave tRNA(fMet) and thus down-regulate protein synthesis. VapB contains an N-terminal  DNA-binding SpoVT-AbrB domain ([interpro:IPR007159]) and inhibits VapC by binding to the VapC PIN domain via its C-terminal domain.</p>\n\n<p>The structure of VapBC complex was determined ([pdbe:3TND]), revealing a large globular hetero-octameric assembly with SpoVT/AbrB-type DNA-binding domains of VapB at each end [[cite:PUB00151271]]. VapBC is the first example of a TA system containing an SpoVT/AbrB-type DNA-binding domain. The DNA-binding motif in VapBC forms through homodimerization of the antitoxin, and it may therefore be one of the main determinants for whether TA complexes form tetramers or octamers.</p>\n\n<p>This entry also includes VapB2 from Haemophilus influenzae ([swissprot:Q4QLV9]) [[cite:PUB00057856], [cite:PUB00105793]], and from Rickettsia felis ([swissprot:Q4UNB3]) [[cite:PUB00141764]]. It seems unrelated to proteins called VapB in Mycobacterium tuberculosis ([interpro:IPR011660]).</p>", "llm" false, "checked" false, "updated" false}], :is-reviewed-llm false, :representative-structure nil, :overlaps-with [{"accession" "IPR037914", "name" "SpoVT-AbrB domain superfamily", "type" "homologous_superfamily"}], :member-databases {"ncbifam" {"NF040493" "type II toxin-antitoxin system VapB family antitoxin"}}, :is-updated-llm false, :name {"name" "Antitoxin VapB2-like", "short" "Anti_VapB2-like"}, :wikipedia nil, :source-database "interpro", :type "family", :counters {"structures" 4, "domain_architectures" 0, "proteomes" 646, "taxa" 4837, "subfamilies" 0, "interactions" 0, "matches" 4944,